passages.text: APAC Conviction List - Directors' Cut: Sept Update. We add Eastroc, Disco, NYPCB, and Japan Exchange Group to the APAC Conviction List whilst removing MediaTek and Nari Tech. For Eastroc, Leaf Liu expects the company to further expand its flagship energy drinks business while transforming into a diversified beverage company through the ramp- up of new products. For Disco, while the market still seems to be skeptical about a meaningful step- up in their shipment figures, Shuhei Nakamura believes the inflection point is close, where Disco's shipments will re- accelerate, driven by new growth drivers such as hybrid bonding. For NYPCB, Chao Wang expects non- NVDA ABF substrate pricing to increase by 5- 10% per quarter from 4Q25 to 4Q26 due to supply shortages, far exceeding the market consensus of a 3- 5% hike in 4Q25 only. Chao believes NYPCB is poised to be a key beneficiary of the pricing uptrend. For Japan Exchange, Gurpreet Singh Sahi expects three catalysts to drive the stock - 1) collateral related interest income offers EPS upside, 2) new FX derivatives to add revenue stream, and 3) bottoming out of JP corporate earnings cuts to boost cash average daily turnover. Michael Snaith

BYD - 2Q25 Earnings Review: Below expectations; expect unit profit to recover in 2H - Buy. BYD reported 2Q25 results with revenue/gross margin missing GSe by - 6%/- 1.8pp. Based on our unit profit analysis, we estimate BYD's domestic unit profit was Rmb523 in 2Q25 (vs. Rmb5.8k in 1Q25), with qoq decline mainly due to: (1) Rmb4.4k higher BOM cost of autopilot version models, in line with our expectation; (2) Rmb2.9k 1- month 618 promotion in June; (3) Rmb666 red packet to dealers. Among these factors, (1) is recurring while (2) & (3) are one- offs. As prices become stabilized under the government's "anti- involution" guidance, we expect unit profit in the domestic market to recover to Rmb4.4k in 3Q25E and Rmb5.0k in 4Q25E. Factoring in declining domestic market share, we lower 2025E- 27E volume estimates to 5.0m- 6.0mn units (from 5.5mn- 6.8m previously), cut our 2025E- 27E net income by 12% - 21%, and reduce our 12m TPs to Rmb133/HK\\$130. Tina Hou Weichai Power - Better 2H25 outlook, embracing new energy transition and committed shareholder return enhancement - Buy (on CL). Weichai hosted an analyst briefing call post its 2Q25 results. Key takeaways from the call include: 1) strong

rebound in LNG engine sales volume in Aug; 2) robust outlook for large- bore engines reaffirmed, with capacity expansion plan on track (by \(50 - 100\%\) ); 3) Weichai was disciplined on pricing strategy against intensified competition in 1H, which resulted in engine share losses; 4) e- powertrain business could see 2- 3x increase both in sales into 2H25 and could emerge as a solid offset to the engine TAM erosion from electrification over the medium- to- long term. We expect earnings to catch up with the HDT cyclical inflection into 2H and Aug preliminary HDT sales data pointed to a solid rebound in LNG HDT demand (see our note). 12m TP of HK\$21/Rmb20.50. Nick Zheng

AccoTest - OSAT Capex cycle recovery and product migration to drive growth ahead - Buy. Accotest reported 2Q25 net income beat our/ BBG consensus by \(29\% /20\%\) reflecting OSAT capex recovery and Accotest's product lines expansion. Management is positive on order and revenues growth momentum in 2H25, supported by capex cycle recovery, overseas market growth, and product expansion to address demand from data center/ automotive market, affirming our constructive view on Accotest. We are positive on the company's comprehensive offerings from analog/ mixed signal testers to high- end digital/ SoC testers, meanwhile expanding to in- house ASIC for testing system. Maintain Buy with 12m TP up to Rmb245. Allen Chang

OmniVision - Vehicle CIS ramp- up and automotive new products in expansion - Buy. OmniVision (previously known as Will Semi) announced 2Q25 results in line with guidance with revenues growth at \(16\%\) YoY, driven by growth of automotive CIS and ramp- up of CIS from new products (panoramic camera, action camera etc.). Despite slower smartphone CIS growth in 1H25 on product transition, management expects to see new products (for example, 50Mpx sensor with 1.6μm large pixels) ramp up in 2H25E, and the company is also working on 200Mpx CIS targeting flagship models. Automotive CIS revenues contribution was up to \(37\%\) of total CIS business in 1H25, and management is positive on growth ahead riding on specification upgrade of new vehicle models, supported by the company's accelerated iteration. 12m TP of Rmb191. Allen Chang

Rakuten Bank - Raise GSe/TP to reflect BOJ rate hike/deposit costs - Buy. We revise our earnings estimates for Rakuten Bank, raising our FY3/26- FY3/28 net profit forecasts by \(7\% /12\% /13\%\) , as we now incorporate a policy rate increase (from \(0.50\%\) to \(0.75\%\) ) in January 2026, as forecast by our economists. While we reflect some deposit acquisition costs due to preferential interest rates on ordinary deposits (deposit yield up 2- 3 bp qoq) introduced in July 2025, we forecast continued double- digit (\%) net profit growth of \(+36\% / + 25\% / + 23\%\) yoy for FY3/26- FY3/28. We raise our 12m TP by \(48\%\) to ¥8,900. Makoto Kuroda

HG Tech - Incremental strength from customer capex bodes well for transceiver demand - Buy. HG Tech's optical transceivers mainly supply to local CSPs and equipment customers. Recent CSP capex strength and outlook (e.g. BABA) bring incremental strength to HG Tech's transceiver growth outlook, in our view, thus removing an overhang on demand sustainability (due to previous concerns over foreign AI chip constraint). With this, we are more positive on HG Tech's transceiver shipment

momentum into 2H25\~2027E with upward revision of \(3\% \sim 8\%\) in our net profit estimates. We now expect \(41\% QoQ\) growth in 3Q25E to align with the company's capacity per month (800k units). \(QmTP\) raised to Rmb81 from Rmb71. Jin Guo

Giant Biogene - NDR takeaways: Resilient consumer sentiment observed - Buy. We hosted Giant Biogene's CFO, Board secretary & CPO and IR team in HK. Overall, we walked away \(30\%\) more confidence of normalized growth into Double 11 given 1) intact consumer sentiment matrix (i.e., 35- 40% repeated purchase, 60% new consumer mix, and limited negative sentiment measurement index on RED), 2) above expected new star SKUs/product series and offline penetration offsetting the slower online growth of single- use- essence short term, and 3) mgmt's constructive tone on KOL resumption with execution details backed by adequate budget to spend. Sun Jian, the top tier KOL on Douyin, just resumed livestreaming on Aug 31 of Comfy's star SKU, Luminous Facial Cream, with GMV achieved above expectation, per mgmt. 12m TP of HK\$71. Cathy Chen

Mengniu Dairy - NDR takeaways: Strong 2B sales momentum into 2H - Buy. We hosted Mengniu NDR in Singapore on Sep 1st. Key takeaways include: 1) Management guided MSD- HSD \(0\) top line decline in FY25, but expected overall liquid milk to decline slightly with narrowing trend in 2H25 vs. 1H25 (- 11%). The company remains cautious on the gifting demand trend for mid autumn festival in 3Q and also for 4Q due to a later Chinese new year on calendar shift; 2) 2B business as a key highlight: Mengniu expected its 2B overall sales to reach c.Rmb10bn in 2025E (DD% topline contribution) with DD% yoy growth rate. 12m TP of HK\$22. Leaf Liu

Hyperstrong - 2Q25 earnings beat on volume, yet margin headwinds likely came stronger than expected - Downgrade to Neutral. Hyperstrong released its 2Q25 results with NP and revenue beating GSe by \(21\% /27\%\) . We attribute the 2Q25 earnings beat to stronger than expected sales volume albeit with investor concerns on mandatory BESS installation termination. Beyond the volume strengths, we estimate Hyperstrong's 2Q25 unit GP lowered to Rmb75/kWh from 1Q25 unit GP Rmb102/kWh, below GSe of Rmb110/kWh. As we elaborated in our initiation report, we recognize the uncertainties from challenges due to competitiveness and hence assigned prudent margin assumptions for Hyperstrong. With 2Q25 results, we believe the margin pressure is being validated. Following a \(\sim 70\%\) share price gain in the past 2 months, we downgrade the stock to Neutral. 12m TP of Rmb120. Eric Shen

China Feihe - Lower guidance; focusing on healthier channel mix - downgrade to Neutral. Feihe reported 1H25 earnings on Aug 28, with sales/NP decreased by \(9.4\% /47\%\) yoy. The company further guided down full- year sales to Rmb21bn (incl. VAT tax) or c. Rmb19bn (post VAT, decline yoy by DD%) with continued destocking into 3Q and a delay in super premium+ product launches. While we recognize the company's efforts in product mix enhancement, more resilient online growth, and steady IMF GPM, we expect further destocking into end- 2025 and more marketing dollars going forward to
regain market share. We downgrade Feihe to Neutral from Buy as competition dynamics remain our main concern of its topline/bottom line performance into 2H. 12m TP is lowered to HK\$4.30. Leaf Liu

Denghai Seeds - Earnings Review: 1H25A below expectation; Headwind from corn seeds ahead - Downgrade to Sell. Denghai's 1H25A was below our expectations, mostly on higher SG&A. We expect increasing pricing challenges for major corn seed producers in the 25/26 crop season, driven by \(34\%\) of excess industry supply produced in the 24/25 crop year leading to ongoing destocking pressure, combined with lower corn prices. Accordingly, we see risk of lower earnings for Denghai, given most of its profit comes from corn seeds. On biotech seeds, we see the magnitude of the benefit for Denghai would be milder versus its major peers, given its high exposure to regions where competition is most intense. Downgrade to Sell, 12m TP of Rmb8. Trina Chen

Europe Strategy - Investing in Europe's moment. European equities had a stellar start to the year benefiting from under- positioning, relatively low valuation and a dramatic change in Germany's fiscal path. But since March, STOXX Europe has moved sideways as a function of tariff news and disappointing earnings. We continue to see several areas supportive of Europe stocks, such as improving European economies in 2026 and 2027, low positioning (especially by domestic investors), inexpensive valuation vs. other assets, and a growing desire to diversify away from US exposure. Rolling forward our European index targets, we forecast \(5\%\) price and \(8\%\) total return over 12 months. We continue to advocate a mix of cyclicals and defensives with OWs in Banks, Telecoms, Tech and Retailers and UW in Autos, Chemicals and Energy. Sharon Bell

The Goldman Sachs Factor Profile provides investment context for a stock by comparing key attributes to the market (i.e. our universe of rated stocks) and its sector peers. The four key attributes depicted are: Growth, Financial Returns, Multiple (e.g. valuation) and Integrated (a composite of Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple). Growth, Financial Returns and Multiple are calculated by using normalized ranks for specific metrics for each stock. The normalized ranks for the metrics are then averaged and converted into percentiles for the relevant attribute. The precise calculation of each metric may vary depending on the fiscal year, industry and region, but the standard approach is as follows:

Growth is based on a stock's forward- looking sales growth, EBITDA growth and EPS growth (for financial stocks, only EPS and sales growth), with a higher percentile indicating a higher growth company. Financial Returns is based on a stock's forward- looking ROE, ROCE and CROCI (for financial stocks, only ROE), with a higher percentile indicating a company with higher financial returns. Multiple is based on a stock's forward- looking P/E, P/B, price/dividend (P/D), EV/EBITDA, EV/FCF and EV/Debt Adjusted Cash Flow (DACF) (for financial stocks, only P/E, P/B and P/D), with a higher percentile indicating a stock trading at a higher multiple. The Integrated percentile is calculated as the average of the Growth percentile, Financial Returns percentile and (100% - Multiple percentile).

Financial Returns and Multiple use the Goldman Sachs analyst forecasts at the fiscal year- end at least three quarters in the future. Growth uses inputs for the fiscal year at least seven quarters in the future compared with the year at least three quarters in the future (on a per- share basis for all metrics).
For a more detailed description of how we calculate the GS Factor Profile, please contact your GS representative.

Across our global coverage, we examine stocks using an M&A framework, considering both qualitative factors and quantitative factors (which may vary across sectors and regions) to incorporate the potential that certain companies could be acquired. We then assign a M&A rank as a means of scoring companies under our rated coverage from 1 to 3, with 1 representing high (30%- 50%) probability of the company becoming an acquisition target, 2 representing medium (15%- 30%) probability and 3 representing low (0%- 15%) probability. For companies ranked 1 or 2, in line with our standard departmental guidelines we incorporate an M&A component into our target price. M&A rank of 3 is considered immaterial and therefore does not factor into our price target, and may or may not be discussed in research.

Buy (B), Neutral (N), Sell (S) Analysts recommend stocks as Buys or Sells for inclusion on various regional Investment Lists. Being assigned a Buy or Sell on an Investment List is determined by a stock's total return potential relative to its coverage universe. Any stock not assigned as a Buy or a Sell on an Investment List with an active rating (i.e., a stock that is not Rating Suspended, Not Rated, Early- Stage Biotech, Coverage Suspended or Not Covered), is deemed Neutral. Each region manages Regional Conviction Lists, which are selected from Buy rated stocks on the respective region's Investment Lists and represent investment recommendations focused on the size of the total return potential and/or the likelihood of the realization of the return across their respective areas of coverage. The addition or removal of stocks from such Conviction Lists are managed by the Investment Review Committee or other designated committee in each respective region and do not represent a change in the analysts' investment rating for such stocks.

Total return potential represents the upside or downside differential between the current share price and the price target, including all paid or anticipated dividends, expected during the time horizon associated with the price target. Price targets are required for all covered stocks. The total return potential, price target and associated time horizon are stated in each report adding or reiterating an Investment List membership.
